      <div resp="part:emfr" type="translation">
        <p n="1">
   				Prosperity! Fortune!
   			</p>
        <p n="1" rend="stanza">
   				...
   			</p>
        <p n="2" rend="stanza">
   				...
   			</p>
      </div>
      <div source="bib:Hultzsch1902-1903_06" type="translation">
        <p n="1">
   				Hail! Prosperity!
   			</p>
        <p n="1" rend="stanza">
   				In (the year) twice five (i.e. ten), which was engraved on palm-leaves,<note>I.e. with which all documents issued at this time had to begin.</note> (from) the year when (the name of) Catti, the king of the Kāṭavas, was entered on a gold leaf,<note>This seems to refer to some custom observed at the coronation of a king; compare <hi rend="italic">South,-Ind. Inscr.</hi> Vol. III. p. 135 and note 2.</note>― Pallavamārāyaṉ of enduring fame, who is respected by (all) the inhabitants of the world, having freed (the villagers) of hunger, caused to be built also a sluice, composed of stones, for the water-tank at Taṇṭalam.
   			</p>
        <p n="2" rend="stanza">
   				The lord of the beautiful goddess of the (lotus) flower (i.e. Lakshmī), Pallavamārāyaṉ, who is beloved by the excellent goddess of the Tamiḻ country, graciously constructed a sluice for the tank at Taṇṭalam in Pōḷiyūr-nāṭu.
   			</p>
      </div>
